Abstract

This volume presents biology as the science of organized matter processing information. Building directly upon the mathematical foundations of Volume I, the physical laws of Volume II, and the chemical principles of Volume III, we derive the structures, processes, and dynamics that characterize living systems. Life is not treated as a collection of empirical observations but as an emergent phenomenon governed by thermodynamics, kinetics, information theory, and evolutionary dynamics.

The unifying thesis is that living systems are stable, far‑from‑equilibrium structures that acquire, store, process, and transmit information to maintain themselves against entropy. From protein folding to ecosystem dynamics, every biological phenomenon is analyzed through this lens.

The volume is structured hierarchically: physical foundations → molecular information processing → genetic systems → cellular thermodynamics → networks and regulation → evolutionary dynamics → neural computation → ecosystems → origins and open problems. Each section provides the minimal mathematical framework necessary to understand the corresponding level of biological organization.

This is the fourth layer of the Civilization Codec, bridging the molecular world of Volume III to the technological and civilizational layers of Volumes V and VI.

