Summary of Part I

We have established the physical foundations of life:

1. Water: Hydrogen bonding ($E_{\text{HB}} \approx 5\text{--}10 k_B T$), dielectric constant ($\epsilon \approx 80$), hydrophobic effect ($\Delta G = \gamma \Delta A$), and proton hopping ($D_{\text{H⁺}} \approx 9.3 \times 10^{-5}$ cm²/s) provide the solvent properties essential for life.
2. Interfaces: Surface tension ($\gamma \approx 72$ mN/m) and the Young-Laplace equation ($\Delta P = \gamma(1/R_1 + 1/R_2)$) determine membrane mechanics and cell shape.
3. Stochastic physics: Langevin equation ($m\ddot{x} = -\gamma\dot{x} + \xi(t)$), Fokker-Planck equation ($\partial_t P = -\partial_x(FP/\gamma) + D\partial_x^2 P$), and Kramer's escape rate ($k = (\omega_0/2\pi)e^{-\Delta E/k_B T}$) describe the noisy environment cells inhabit.
4. Thermal ratchets: Life exploits noise through rectification mechanisms, achieving directed motion with efficiency $\eta \approx 50\text{--}60\%$.
5. Self-assembly: Thermodynamic driving forces ($\Delta G = \Delta H - T\Delta S$), nucleation theory ($n^* = (2\gamma/3\Delta\mu)^3$), and the Helfrich Hamiltonian ($E = \int [(\kappa/2)(2H-H_0)^2 + \bar{\kappa}K] dA$) explain spontaneous organization.
6. Crowding: Excluded volume effects alter equilibria ($K_c = K_a (\gamma_A\gamma_B/\gamma_C)$) and kinetics ($D_{\text{eff}} = D_0 e^{-\alpha\phi}$)—the cell is not a dilute solution.
7. Biopolymer mechanics: Persistence length ($\langle \mathbf{t}(s)\cdot\mathbf{t}(s+\Delta s) \rangle = e^{-\Delta s/L_p}$) and worm-like chain model ($F = (k_B T/L_p)[(1/4)(1-x/L_c)^{-2} - 1/4 + x/L_c]$) describe the structural materials of the cell.

These are the hardware specifications for the living machine. In Part II, we will see how this hardware runs the software of life—information processing in proteins and genes.

Part II — Molecular Information Processing

