Chapter 9 — Protein Information: Synthesis

9.1 Information Flow in the Central Dogma

The central dogma of molecular biology describes information flow:

\text{DNA} \xrightarrow{\text{transcription}} \text{RNA} \xrightarrow{\text{translation}} \text{Protein}

At each step, information is transferred but also transformed. The genetic code maps 64 codons to 20 amino acids—a many-to-one mapping that introduces redundancy.

Adiguzel (2017) proposed that the information lost in codon degeneracy is compensated by conformational information in proteins . A protein's sequence specifies not only a unique fold but also an ensemble of conformations around that fold. This conformational entropy:

S_{\text{conf}} = -k_B \sum_i p_i \ln p_i

where $p_i$ are probabilities of different conformational substates, adds information that balances the information content of the coding mRNA.

9.2 Information Theory and Protein Design

The Shannon entropy of protein sequences provides a measure of their information content . This has implications for protein design: the number of sequences that can fold into a given structure is much less than the total number of possible sequences.

The designability of a structure is related to its symmetry and complexity. Simple, symmetric folds (like TIM barrels) can be realized by many sequences; complex, irregular folds are more sequence-specific.

9.3 The Protein as a Communication Channel

Viewing the protein as a communication channel, the input is the amino acid sequence, the output is the functional protein (folded, active), and the channel capacity is determined by the folding process and cellular environment.

The fidelity of the channel—the probability that a given sequence yields the correct fold—is remarkably high for natural proteins but can be reduced by mutations, leading to misfolding diseases.

9.4 From Information to Function

The ultimate output of protein information processing is biological function: catalysis, signaling, transport, structure. Each function imposes constraints on the sequence and structure.

The relationship between sequence, structure, and function can be quantified using mutual information. For a family of homologous proteins:

I(\text{sequence}; \text{function}) = H(\text{function}) - H(\text{function}|\text{sequence})

This measures how much information the sequence provides about function—a key quantity for predicting function from sequence.

