Chapter 14 — The Eigen Paradox and Information Limits

14.1 The Error Threshold

Manfred Eigen (1971) identified a fundamental limit on the information content of replicating molecules. For a genome of length $L$ replicating with mutation rate $\mu$ per base, the information can be maintained only if:

\mu L < \ln \sigma

where $\sigma$ is the superiority of the master sequence—its selective advantage over the mutant distribution .

If this condition is violated, the system enters error catastrophe: mutations accumulate faster than selection can remove them, and information is lost. The critical genome length is:

L_{\text{max}} < \frac{\ln \sigma}{\mu}

14.2 The Paradox of Early Life

Early life likely had high mutation rates due to primitive, error‑prune replication mechanisms. Experimental measurements of non‑enzymatic template-directed polymerization show average mutation rates of $7.6\%$ per base . At such rates, the maximum sustainable genome length would be:

L_{\text{max}} < \frac{\ln(2)}{0.076} \approx 9 \text{ nucleotides}

assuming a modest superiority $\sigma = 2$. Yet the simplest self‑replicating systems likely required genomes of at least 50–100 nucleotides. This is the Eigen paradox of the origin of life .

14.3 Solutions to the Paradox

Several mechanisms can extend the error threshold:

Post‑mismatch stalling: When a mismatch occurs, polymerization slows dramatically. Experimental studies of non‑enzymatic replication show that most mismatches decrease the rate of primer extension by more than 2 orders of magnitude relative to matched controls .

This stalling creates a kinetic advantage for accurate copies: they complete replication faster and can begin the next round sooner. The modified error threshold including stalling is:

\mu L < \ln \sigma + \ln\left(1 + \frac{k_{\text{correct}}}{k_{\text{error}}}\right)

where $k_{\text{correct}}/k_{\text{error}}$ is the stalling factor. With stalling factors of 100‑fold, the maximum genome length increases substantially .

Truncated selection: If sequences beyond a certain Hamming distance from the master are inviable (lethal mutants), the error threshold can be extended further. Statistical physics models show that lethal mutants and truncated selection together can resolve the paradox, allowing genome lengths of thousands of nucleotides even with high mutation rates .

Compartimentalization: Encapsulation of replicating molecules in protocells links genotype and phenotype, enabling group selection and reducing the effective error rate.

14.4 Modern Error Thresholds

In modern organisms with sophisticated replication machinery, mutation rates are much lower:

Organism Mutation rate per base per replication Maximum genome length
RNA viruses $10^{-3} - 10^{-5}$ 10⁴ - 10⁵ bases
DNA viruses $10^{-6} - 10^{-8}$ 10⁵ - 10⁶ bp
Bacteria $10^{-9} - 10^{-10}$ 10⁶ - 10⁷ bp
Eukaryotes $10^{-9} - 10^{-11}$ 10⁷ - 10¹⁰ bp

These values reflect the co‑evolution of replication fidelity and genome complexity. The development of proofreading and mismatch repair enabled the expansion of genome size and the evolution of complex organisms.

14.5 The Codec Implication: Information Capacity Limits

The Eigen paradox defines the fundamental bandwidth of genetic information. The maximum rate at which information can be reliably transmitted across generations is:

C = \frac{\ln \sigma}{\mu} \text{ bits per generation}

This is a physical limit imposed by thermodynamics and kinetics, analogous to the Shannon channel capacity in communication theory. Life operates near this limit, balancing the need for accurate replication (low $\mu$) with the need for evolutionary adaptability (some variation must be allowed).

The evolution of error correction mechanisms—proofreading, mismatch repair, and eventually sexual reproduction with recombination—can be viewed as a progressive increase in the channel capacity of the genetic system, enabling the transmission of larger and more complex genomes.

