We have established the thermodynamic foundations of cellular life:

1. ATP as energy currency: Phosphoanhydride bonds store 30–60 kJ/mol under physiological conditions. Energy coupling allows endergonic reactions to proceed by linking them to ATP hydrolysis.
2. Chemiosmotic theory: Electron transport chains generate a proton motive force ($\Delta p = \Delta \Psi - 2.303RT\Delta\text{pH}/F$) of approximately 200 mV, storing about 20 kJ/mol per proton.
3. ATP synthase: A rotary motor operating at 75–83% efficiency, converting proton flow into mechanical rotation and then into chemical bond formation. Despite nanoscale dimensions, it operates classically, avoiding quantum uncertainties.
