Chapter 28 — Evolutionary Dynamics in Finite Populations

28.1 The Moran Process

The Moran process models evolution in finite populations with overlapping generations. At each step, one individual reproduces and one dies, maintaining constant population size $N$.

The fixation probability of a single mutant with relative fitness $r$ is:

P_{\text{fix}} = \frac{1 - 1/r}{1 - 1/r^N}

For neutral mutants ($r=1$), $P_{\text{fix}} = 1/N$.

28.2 The Wright-Fisher vs. Moran Comparison

Feature Wright-Fisher Moran
Generations Discrete, non‑overlapping Overlapping, continuous time
Time scaling Generation units 1 unit = $N$ steps
Variance effective size $N$ $N/2$
Fixation time (neutral) $\approx 4N$ generations $\approx N$ Moran steps

28.3 Effective Population Size and Information

The effective population size $N_e$ determines the relative importance of selection versus drift. The product $N_e s$ is the key parameter:

· $N_e s \ll 1$: Drift dominates, neutral evolution
· $N_e s \gg 1$: Selection dominates, deterministic evolution

From an information perspective, $N_e s$ measures the signal-to-noise ratio of selection. Information accumulates only when $N_e s > 1$.

