Chapter 32 — Synaptic Plasticity: The Mechanism of Memory

32.1 Hebb's Postulate

Donald Hebb (1949) proposed the foundational principle of synaptic plasticity: "When an axon of cell A is near enough to excite cell B and repeatedly or persistently takes part in firing it, some growth process or metabolic change takes place in one or both cells such that A's efficiency as one of the cells firing B is increased."

This is often summarized as: "Cells that fire together, wire together."

The simplest mathematical formulation is:

\Delta w_{ij} = \eta \cdot x_i \cdot x_j

where $w_{ij}$ is the synaptic weight from neuron $i$ to neuron $j$, $x_i$ and $x_j$ are their activities, and $\eta$ is a learning rate.

32.2 Spike-Timing-Dependent Plasticity (STDP)

Experimental work in the 1990s revealed that synaptic plasticity depends on the precise timing of pre- and post-synaptic spikes. Spike-timing-dependent plasticity (STDP) has become the dominant model of synaptic modification .

Debanne and Inglebert (2023) review that "STDP is a bidirectional form of synaptic plasticity discovered about 30 years ago and based on the relative timing of pre- and post-synaptic spiking activity with a millisecond precision" .

The standard STDP rule:

\Delta w = \begin{cases}
A_+ e^{-\Delta t / \tau_+} & \text{if } \Delta t > 0 \text{ (pre before post)} \\
-A_- e^{\Delta t / \tau_-} & \text{if } \Delta t < 0 \text{ (post before pre)}
\end{cases}

where $\Delta t = t_{\text{post}} - t_{\text{pre}}$, $A_+$ and $A_-$ are amplitude parameters, and $\tau_+$, $\tau_-$ are time constants.

32.3 STDP and Memory Formation

The role of STDP in memory formation has been extensively studied. Debanne and Inglebert note that "STDP is thought to be involved in the formation of memory" but note a key challenge: "the millisecond-precision spike-timing required for STDP is difficult to reconcile with the much slower timescales of behavioral learning" .

Recent research addresses this through:

· Multiple STDP rules at both excitatory and inhibitory synapses
· Contribution of STDP-like plasticity in memory formation in vivo
· Implementation of STDP rules in artificial neural networks and memristive devices 

32.4 The BCM Rule

The Bienenstock-Cooper-Munro (BCM) rule incorporates a sliding threshold for modification:

\Delta w = \eta \cdot x \cdot y \cdot (y - \theta_M)

where $\theta_M$ is a modification threshold that depends on the average postsynaptic activity. This rule accounts for bidirectional plasticity and stability.

