Chapter 34 — Learning as Information Processing

34.1 The Learning Problem

From an information-theoretic perspective, learning is the process of extracting useful patterns from data. The brain continuously solves this problem across multiple timescales:

· Milliseconds: Sensory processing
· Seconds: Working memory
· Minutes: Short-term adaptation
· Hours to years: Long-term memory

34.2 Supervised Learning in the Brain

While classical supervised learning (backpropagation) is biologically implausible, the brain achieves similar functionality through local learning rules. Predictive coding offers a framework where:

· Top-down predictions are compared with bottom-up sensory input
· Prediction errors drive learning
· Hierarchical representations emerge

34.3 Reinforcement Learning and Dopamine

Dopamine neurons in the midbrain implement a temporal difference learning algorithm:

\delta(t) = r(t) + \gamma V(t+1) - V(t)

where $\delta$ is the prediction error, $r$ is reward, $V$ is value estimate, and $\gamma$ is a discount factor. Dopamine firing correlates with $\delta$, providing a global reinforcement signal.

34.4 Unsupervised Learning

The brain primarily learns without explicit labels. Hebbian plasticity (Section 32.1) implements a form of unsupervised learning that extracts statistical regularities from sensory input. Competitive learning and self-organizing maps capture additional unsupervised mechanisms.

