Chapter 35 — The Information-Theoretic Neuron

35.1 Neural Information Rate

The information transmitted by a single spike train can be quantified using Shannon's mutual information. For a neuron with mean firing rate $r$ and spike train variability, the information rate is bounded by:

R \leq r \log_2\left(1 + \frac{\text{SNR}}{\ln 2}\right) \text{ bits/s}

where SNR is the signal-to-noise ratio of the neural response.

35.2 Population Coding

Neurons work in populations. The joint activity of many neurons can encode far more information than the sum of individuals due to correlations. The population information is:

I_{\text{pop}} = H(\mathbf{x}) - H(\mathbf{x}|\mathbf{s})

where $\mathbf{x}$ is the population response vector and $\mathbf{s}$ is the stimulus.

35.3 Efficient Coding Hypothesis

The efficient coding hypothesis proposes that sensory systems are optimized to transmit maximum information about natural stimuli given biophysical constraints. This leads to predictions about:

· Receptive field properties
· Response nonlinearities
· Adaptation dynamics

35.4 The Metabolic Cost of Information

Neural computation is energetically expensive. The brain consumes approximately 20% of the body's energy despite being only 2% of its mass. The cost per spike is approximately:

E_{\text{spike}} \approx 10^5\text{--}10^6 \text{ ATP molecules}

Comparing to the Landauer limit ($\approx 10 k_B T$ per bit at room temperature), neural computation is remarkably inefficient in thermodynamic terms—but this inefficiency buys speed, reliability, and flexibility.

