Chapter 39 — Biogeochemical Cycles: The Elemental Information Flow

39.1 Box Models of Element Cycles

Biogeochemical cycles describe the movement of chemical elements (C, N, P, S, etc.) through the Earth system—atmosphere, oceans, land, and living organisms. These cycles can be modeled using box models .

For a reservoir with mass $M$ of an element, the mass balance equation is:

\frac{dM}{dt} = \sum \text{inputs} - \sum \text{outputs}

At steady state, $dM/dt = 0$, so inputs equal outputs.

39.2 Residence Time and Response Time

Two fundamental timescales characterize biogeochemical cycles :

Residence time $\tau$ is the average time an atom spends in a reservoir:

\tau = \frac{M}{\text{total output rate}}

Response time $T$ is the time for the system to adjust to a perturbation. For a linear first-order system:

\frac{dM}{dt} = -\frac{M}{\tau} + \text{input}

The response time equals $\tau$.

39.3 The Carbon Cycle as an Information Network

The global carbon cycle can be represented as a network of reservoirs with fluxes between them. Key reservoirs include:

· Atmosphere ($\approx 900$ GtC)
· Terrestrial vegetation ($\approx 600$ GtC)
· Soils ($\approx 1500$ GtC)
· Ocean surface ($\approx 1000$ GtC)
· Deep ocean ($\approx 38,000$ GtC)
· Fossil fuels ($\approx 4000$ GtC)

The fluxes between reservoirs are driven by biological processes (photosynthesis, respiration, decomposition) and physical processes (ocean circulation, volcanic activity).

From an information-theoretic perspective, the carbon cycle represents the planet's "metabolism"—the flow of energy and matter that sustains the biosphere.

39.4 Human Perturbations

Human activities have dramatically altered biogeochemical cycles:

· Carbon: Fossil fuel combustion and deforestation have increased atmospheric CO₂ by 50% since pre-industrial times
· Nitrogen: Haber-Bosch nitrogen fixation for fertilizer now exceeds natural terrestrial fixation
· Phosphorus: Mining of phosphate rock has accelerated phosphorus flow to ecosystems

These perturbations represent information injection into the Earth system, with consequences for climate, biodiversity, and ecosystem functioning.

