Chapter 43 — The Thermodynamic Framework for Abiogenesis

43.1 The Fundamental Question

How did non-living chemistry transition to living systems? This is the question of abiogenesis—the origin of life from non-living matter. Traditional approaches focus on replication, heredity, or molecular specificity. A complementary perspective emphasizes thermodynamics .

43.2 The Reaction Viability Inequality

Prosser (2025) proposed a thermodynamic framework in which the emergence of life is driven by the persistence of reaction pathways that align energetically with fluctuating environmental inputs .

The reaction viability inequality is defined as:

\Delta G_{\text{input}} - \Delta G_{\text{release}} - \Delta G_{\text{resilience}} - \Delta G_{\text{expenditure}} > 0

where:

· $\Delta G_{\text{input}}$ is free energy available from the environment
· $\Delta G_{\text{release}}$ is energy dissipated
· $\Delta G_{\text{resilience}}$ is energy required to maintain structure against perturbations
· $\Delta G_{\text{expenditure}}$ is energy cost of the reaction network

This inequality selects for persistent chemical configurations without invoking heredity or genetic encoding .

43.3 Entropic Dynamics and Local Order

Systems far from equilibrium can simultaneously increase global entropy while supporting localized chemical order. The total entropy production rate is:

\frac{dS}{dt} = \frac{d_eS}{dt} + \frac{d_iS}{dt} > 0

Local order emerges when:

\frac{d_eS_{\text{local}}}{dt} < 0 \quad \text{and} \quad \frac{d_iS_{\text{local}}}{dt} > \left|\frac{d_eS_{\text{local}}}{dt}\right|

Prosser incorporates "entropic dynamics and spatial constraints into an augmented persistence function, showing that systems far from equilibrium can simultaneously increase global entropy while supporting localized chemical order" .

43.4 The Thermodynamic Abiogenesis Likelihood Model (TALM)

These refinements lead to the Thermodynamic Abiogenesis Likelihood Model (TALM), a probabilistic extension that estimates the likelihood of persistence-driven selection under diverse prebiotic and planetary scenarios .

TALM provides:

1. A framework for comparing different prebiotic environments
2. Predictions about conditions favoring abiogenesis
3. A testable, general theory for the origin of life grounded in physical law

"This framework redefines the conditions under which life-like organization may emerge and provides a testable, general theory for abiogenesis grounded in physical law" .

