Chapter 48 — Life Detection: Identifying Biosignatures

48.1 The Challenge of Detecting Life

How do we determine whether a sample—from ancient Earth rocks or another planet—contains evidence of life? Traditional approaches look for:

· Fossils (preserved structures)
· Biomolecules (DNA, lipids, amino acids)
· Isotopic ratios (preferential incorporation of light isotopes)

These approaches require intact structures or molecules, limiting their applicability to highly degraded samples.

48.2 Machine Learning for Biosignature Detection

A groundbreaking study published in Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences developed a new approach using machine learning to detect life .

Researchers analyzed more than 400 samples from:

· Ancient sediments
· Fossils
· Modern plants and animals
· Fungi
· Meteorites

Using pyrolysis–gas chromatography–mass spectrometry, they released molecular fragments and analyzed the complex chemical patterns with machine learning .

The result: "a system capable of distinguishing material left behind by life from non-biological samples with more than 90 percent accuracy" .

48.3 The Distribution-Based Approach

Rather than looking for specific molecules, the algorithm examines the distribution of what's present .

Co-author Dr. Robert Hazen explained: "For the very first time, we're just looking for a distribution function. That allows us to be much more general when examining highly degraded samples with very little information" .

This approach detected biosignatures dating back 3.3 billion years—almost twice the previous limit of around 1.7 billion years .

The team also found "molecular evidence that oxygen-producing photosynthesis was occurring at least 2.5 billion years ago, extending the chemical record of photosynthesis by more than 800 million years" .

48.4 Beyond Simple Life Detection

The algorithm goes beyond a simple life-versus-no-life test :

· It can already distinguish photosynthetic from non-photosynthetic organisms
· It can separate eukaryotes from prokaryotes
· It offers potential for identifying different metabolic strategies

Co-author Dr. Anirudh Prabhu noted: "AI didn't just help us analyze data faster, it allowed us to make sense of messy, degraded chemical data. It opens the door to exploring ancient and alien environments with a fresh lens, guided by patterns we might not even know to look for ourselves" .

48.5 Applications to Mars Exploration

The technique could be deployed on Mars in two ways :

1. Sample return: Analyzing returned Martian samples in terrestrial laboratories
2. In situ analysis: A rover carrying a suite of instruments could apply the same machine-learning approach directly on the Martian surface

The team has received NASA funding to develop such an instrument package .

