Chapter 49 — Synthetic Biology and Artificial Life

49.1 The Minimal Genome

What is the minimal set of genes required for life? The J. Craig Venter Institute synthesized Mycoplasma mycoides with a minimal genome of 473 genes [citation from Part VI summary]. This "minimal cell" can grow and divide in laboratory conditions.

The minimal genome represents the essential information for bacterial life—the core operating system of a cell.

49.2 Genetic Circuits as Programmable Logic

Synthetic biologists have engineered genetic circuits that perform Boolean logic:

\text{Output} = f(\text{Input}_1, \text{Input}_2, \ldots, \text{Input}_n)

Examples include:

· Toggle switch: Bistable memory element [citation from Part V]
· Repressilator: Oscillatory circuit
· AND gate: Requires two inputs for output
· Biocomputer: Multiple logic gates integrated for computation

49.3 Directed Evolution as Algorithmic Optimization

Directed evolution iteratively improves proteins or pathways through:

1. Diversification: Creating libraries of variants (mutagenesis)
2. Selection: Identifying improved variants (screening or selection)
3. Amplification: Propagating successful variants

The rate of improvement follows:

\frac{d\bar{z}}{dt} \approx 2N\mu s \bar{z}

where $\bar{z}$ is mean fitness, $N$ is population size, $\mu$ is mutation rate, and $s$ is selection coefficient.

49.4 Artificial Life Criteria

What constitutes artificial life? Proposed criteria include:

1. Autopoiesis: Self-maintenance through internal processes
2. Evolution: Capacity for adaptation over generations
3. Cognition: Information processing and response to environment

Mark Bedau's continuum considers systems as "living" to the degree they exhibit:

· Metabolism: Energy transduction
· Homeostasis: Self-regulation
· Information processing: Response to stimuli
· Replication: Production of offspring

